[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 9.9: Surgical Video Analysis
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Research/Pilot · **Estimated Cost:** ~$2.50–$8.00 per procedure (cloud inference)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A surgeon finishes a laparoscopic cholecystectomy. It took 47 minutes. Somewhere in those 47 minutes, there was a moment where the critical view of safety was achieved (or wasn't), a moment where the cystic duct was clipped, and a moment where the dissection got close to the common bile duct. If something went wrong, if there's a bile duct injury that shows up three days later, the only record of what happened is the surgeon's operative note ("procedure performed without complication") and a video file sitting on a hard drive in the OR that nobody will ever watch unless there's a lawsuit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is the state of surgical quality in 2026. We record thousands of hours of surgical video every week across major health systems, and almost none of it gets reviewed. The video just accumulates. It's like having security cameras that nobody monitors and nobody rewinds unless something terrible happens.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The waste here isn't just informational. It's educational and operational. Surgical trainees could learn from annotated videos showing exactly when and how experienced surgeons achieve critical landmarks. Quality committees could identify patterns: which cases take longer, which have more bleeding, which deviate from standard technique. Credentialing boards could objectively assess competency instead of relying on case logs and subjective evaluations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m But watching video is expensive. A 45-minute procedure takes 45 minutes to review. Multiply that by hundreds of cases per week, and no human workforce can keep up. The only way to make surgical video useful at scale is to have machines watch it first: identifying phases, detecting instruments, recognizing anatomy, and flagging moments that matter.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is surgical video analysis. It's one of the most technically demanding computer vision problems in healthcare, and it's still largely in the research phase. But the architectures are maturing, the datasets are growing, and the first clinical applications are starting to appear.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: How Machines Watch Surgery
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Video Understanding vs. Image Classification
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Most medical imaging AI works on single frames: one X-ray, one CT slice, one pathology tile. Surgical video analysis is fundamentally different because it requires temporal reasoning. A single frame from a cholecystectomy might show a grasper holding tissue, but you can't tell from that frame alone whether the surgeon is in the dissection phase or the extraction phase. Context comes from what happened before and what happens next.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This means the models need to process sequences of frames, maintaining some representation of "what's been happening" as they move through the video. The field borrows heavily from action recognition in general computer vision (the same technology that lets YouTube identify whether someone is skateboarding or cooking), but with domain-specific challenges that make surgery much harder.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Core Tasks
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Surgical video analysis isn't one problem. It's a family of related tasks, each with different difficulty levels:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Phase recognition.** Identifying which phase of the procedure is currently happening. A laparoscopic cholecystectomy has roughly seven phases: preparation, Calot's triangle dissection, clipping and cutting, gallbladder dissection, gallbladder packaging, cleaning and coagulation, and specimen extraction. Phase recognition is the most mature task, with models achieving 85-92% accuracy on benchmark datasets.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool detection and tracking.** Identifying which surgical instruments are present in the frame and where they are. This is essentially object detection applied to surgical tools: graspers, scissors, clip appliers, cautery hooks. The challenge is that tools are often partially occluded by tissue, covered in blood, or only partially in frame.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Anatomy recognition.** Identifying anatomical structures in the surgical field. In a cholecystectomy, that means the cystic duct, cystic artery, common bile duct, liver bed, and gallbladder. This is harder than tool detection because anatomy doesn't have consistent shapes or colors across patients, and the visual appearance changes dramatically as dissection progresses.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Activity recognition.** Understanding what action is being performed: cutting, grasping, retracting, cauterizing, clipping. This combines tool detection with motion analysis.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Critical event detection.** Identifying specific moments of clinical significance: achievement of the critical view of safety, bleeding events, near-misses with important structures. This is the highest-value task and also the hardest, because it requires integrating phase, tool, anatomy, and activity understanding.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Model Architectures
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The dominant approach combines two stages:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Spatial feature extraction.** A convolutional neural network (CNN) or vision transformer processes individual frames to extract visual features. This is the "what's in this frame" step. Common backbones include ResNet-50, EfficientNet, or increasingly, vision transformers like ViT. These are typically pretrained on ImageNet and then fine-tuned on surgical data.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Temporal modeling.** A sequence model processes the stream of per-frame features to capture temporal patterns. The most common choices are:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Temporal Convolutional Networks (TCNs):** Apply 1D convolutions over the time dimension. Good at capturing local temporal patterns. The TeCNO architecture is a well-known example.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Transformers:** Self-attention over the temporal sequence. Better at long-range dependencies (understanding that what happened 5 minutes ago affects the current phase). Trans-SVNet is a representative architecture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **LSTMs/GRUs:** Recurrent networks that maintain a hidden state. Older approach, still used but increasingly replaced by transformers.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The two-stage approach (CNN + temporal model) is called a "feature extraction then temporal modeling" pipeline. Some newer architectures do end-to-end video processing with 3D convolutions or video transformers, but the two-stage approach remains dominant because it's more computationally tractable for long surgical videos.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why This Is Hard
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Video length.** A typical procedure is 30-120 minutes at 25-30 fps. That's 45,000 to 216,000 frames. You can't process every frame through a large model in real time. Practical systems sample frames (every 1-5 seconds) or use lightweight models for initial processing with heavier models for segments of interest.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Visual complexity.** The surgical field is wet, reflective, and constantly changing. Smoke from cautery obscures the view. Blood pools and spreads. Tissue deforms as it's manipulated. Lighting changes as the camera moves. These aren't edge cases; they're the normal operating conditions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Variability across surgeons and patients.** Two surgeons performing the same procedure will use different techniques, different instrument preferences, and different approaches to the same anatomy. Patient anatomy varies. BMI affects visibility. Prior surgery creates adhesions that change the visual landscape entirely.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Annotation cost.** Training these models requires frame-level or segment-level annotations from expert surgeons. A single annotated cholecystectomy video might take a surgeon 2-4 hours to label. Building a dataset of hundreds of annotated procedures is enormously expensive. This is why public datasets like Cholec80 (80 cholecystectomy videos with phase and tool annotations) are so important to the field.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Class imbalance.** Some phases are very short (clipping takes seconds) while others are long (dissection takes minutes). Rare events (bleeding, complications) are by definition uncommon. Models tend to be biased toward predicting the majority class unless specifically designed to handle imbalance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Is Now
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Phase recognition on laparoscopic cholecystectomy is the most mature application, with multiple research groups reporting 85-92% frame-level accuracy on Cholec80. Tool detection is similarly mature for common instruments. Anatomy recognition and critical event detection are less mature but advancing rapidly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The gap between research and clinical deployment is significant. Research models work on curated datasets with consistent video quality. Clinical deployment means handling variable camera angles, different OR setups, different laparoscopic systems, and the full diversity of patient anatomy. A few companies have FDA-cleared or CE-marked products for specific narrow applications (primarily phase recognition and critical view of safety assessment in cholecystectomy), but broad clinical deployment is still early.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The pipeline for surgical video analysis has distinct offline and (optionally) real-time paths:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Video Capture] → [Ingest & Store] → [Preprocessing] → [Frame Sampling] → [Feature Extraction] → [Temporal Modeling] → [Post-Processing] → [Results Store] → [Visualization / API]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Video Capture.** Surgical video comes from the laparoscopic camera system, robotic surgery console, or overhead OR cameras. The video is typically recorded by the OR's existing video management system. Getting this video out of the OR and into your analysis pipeline is often the hardest integration challenge, not a technical one but a workflow and governance one.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Ingest and Store.** Raw surgical video files are large (a 60-minute procedure at 1080p is 10-30 GB depending on codec). You need high-throughput, durable storage that can handle these volumes. Videos must be associated with case metadata: procedure type, surgeon, date, patient (de-identified for research pipelines).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Preprocessing.** Normalize video format, resolution, and frame rate. Remove non-surgical segments (camera outside the body, blank screens, title cards). Detect and handle camera occlusion events (lens fogging, blood on the lens). This step is more important than it sounds: garbage in, garbage out.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Frame Sampling.** Extract frames at a fixed interval (typically 1 fps for phase recognition, higher for tool detection). Full frame rate processing is computationally prohibitive for most applications. The sampling rate is a tradeoff between temporal resolution and compute cost.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Feature Extraction.** Run each sampled frame through the spatial backbone (CNN or vision transformer) to produce a feature vector. This is the most compute-intensive step per frame. For offline analysis, this can be batched on GPUs. For real-time applications, you need inference hardware in or near the OR.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Temporal Modeling.** Feed the sequence of feature vectors into the temporal model (TCN, transformer, or LSTM) to produce per-frame predictions (phase labels, tool presence, activity labels). The temporal model is much lighter than the spatial backbone.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Post-Processing.** Smooth predictions (a single frame predicted as "extraction" in the middle of a long "dissection" segment is probably wrong). Apply transition logic (certain phase sequences are impossible). Aggregate frame-level predictions into segment-level annotations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Results Store.** Store the analysis results: phase timeline, tool usage timeline, detected events, confidence scores. Link back to the source video with timestamps for easy retrieval.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Visualization and API.** Provide interfaces for surgeons, quality teams, and researchers to browse results. Timeline views showing phases and events. Video playback synchronized with annotations. Search capabilities ("show me all cases where dissection took longer than 20 minutes").
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon S3 for video storage.** Surgical videos are large, write-once, read-occasionally objects. S3 is the natural fit. Use S3 Intelligent-Tiering: videos are accessed frequently in the first few days (for analysis), then rarely (for audit and research). Lifecycle policies can move older videos to S3 Glacier Deep Archive for long-term retention at minimal cost.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Elemental MediaConvert for preprocessing.** Surgical video arrives in various formats (MPEG-4, H.264, H.265, sometimes proprietary formats from specific OR systems). MediaConvert normalizes everything to a consistent format and resolution before analysis. It also handles frame extraction at specified intervals, producing the sampled frames that feed the ML pipeline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SageMaker for model training and batch inference.** The spatial backbone and temporal model both require GPU training on annotated surgical datasets. SageMaker provides managed training infrastructure with spot instances for cost optimization. For batch analysis of recorded procedures, SageMaker Batch Transform processes videos without maintaining persistent endpoints.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SageMaker Endpoints for real-time inference (optional).** If you need intraoperative analysis (phase recognition during the procedure), you need a persistent GPU endpoint. SageMaker real-time endpoints with GPU instances (ml.g5 family) provide the inference infrastructure. This is expensive and only justified for specific real-time use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Step Functions for pipeline orchestration.** The analysis pipeline has multiple sequential and parallel steps: preprocessing, frame extraction, feature extraction, temporal modeling, post-processing. Step Functions coordinates these steps, handles retries on failure, and provides visibility into pipeline state.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for analysis metadata.** Case metadata, analysis status, and result summaries live in DynamoDB for fast lookup. The full frame-level predictions are too large for DynamoDB and go to S3 as JSON or Parquet files.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon OpenSearch Service for search and discovery.** Surgeons and quality teams need to search across analyzed cases: "show me all cholecystectomies where the dissection phase exceeded 15 minutes" or "find cases with detected bleeding events." OpenSearch indexes the analysis results for flexible querying.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m flowchart TD
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     A[🎥 OR Video System] -->|DICOM/MP4| B[S3 Bucket\nsurgical-videos-raw/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B -->|S3 Event| C[Step Functions\nAnalysis Pipeline]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Transcode| D[MediaConvert\nNormalize + Extract Frames]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     D -->|Frames| E[S3 Bucket\nframes-extracted/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     E -->|Batch| F[SageMaker Batch Transform\nSpatial Feature Extraction]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     F -->|Features| G[S3 Bucket\nfeature-vectors/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     G -->|Batch| H[SageMaker Batch Transform\nTemporal Model Inference]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     H -->|Predictions| I[S3 Bucket\nanalysis-results/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     I --> J[Lambda\nPost-Processing + Index]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     J --> K[DynamoDB\nCase Metadata]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     J --> L[OpenSearch\nSearchable Results]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     L --> M[Web Dashboard\nVisualization]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style B fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style F fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style H fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style K fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon S3, AWS Elemental MediaConvert, Amazon SageMaker, AWS Step Functions, Amazon DynamoDB, Amazon OpenSearch Service, AWS Lambda |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `sagemaker:CreateTransformJob`, `sagemaker:InvokeEndpoint`, `mediaconvert:CreateJob`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:Query`, `states:StartExecution` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed (surgical video is PHI even when de-identified for research; patient identity may be visible in non-laparoscopic views) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS for all buckets; DynamoDB: encryption at rest; OpenSearch: encryption at rest and node-to-node encryption; all transit over TLS; SageMaker: KMS-encrypted training volumes and model artifacts |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: SageMaker endpoints and OpenSearch in VPC with VPC endpoints for S3. No public internet access for inference infrastructure. VPC Flow Logs enabled. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled: log all S3, SageMaker, and DynamoDB API calls for HIPAA audit trail |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **GPU Instances** | SageMaker: ml.g5.xlarge or ml.g5.2xlarge for inference; ml.g5.12xlarge or ml.p4d.24xlarge for training |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Sample Data** | Cholec80 dataset (publicly available, 80 annotated cholecystectomy videos). CholecSeg8k for segmentation. Never use identifiable patient video in dev without IRB approval and proper consent. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Batch inference: ~$2.50-$8.00 per procedure (depending on length and model complexity). Storage: ~$0.50/month per procedure (raw video in Intelligent-Tiering). Training: $500-$5,000 per training run depending on dataset size and GPU hours. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Stores raw video, extracted frames, feature vectors, and analysis results |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Elemental MediaConvert** | Transcodes video to standard format; extracts frames at specified intervals |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Hosts spatial and temporal models for training and inference |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Step Functions** | Orchestrates the multi-step analysis pipeline |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Stores case metadata and analysis summaries |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon OpenSearch Service** | Enables search across analyzed cases by phase duration, events, tools |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Post-processing, indexing, and lightweight orchestration tasks |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Manages encryption keys for all data stores |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Pipeline monitoring, latency metrics, failure alerting |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 1: Video ingestion and metadata registration.** When a surgical video arrives in the system (either pushed from the OR video management system or pulled on a schedule), the pipeline registers it with case metadata and kicks off analysis. The metadata links the video to a procedure type, surgeon, date, and (for clinical use) a de-identified patient reference. Without this registration step, you have video files with no context, and context is everything for downstream search and quality analysis.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION ingest_video(video_file, case_metadata):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Upload the raw video to durable storage.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Surgical videos are large (10-30 GB). Use multipart upload for reliability.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     video_key = "raw-videos/{year}/{month}/{case_id}/{filename}"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     upload video_file to S3 bucket "surgical-videos" at video_key
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         with SSE-KMS encryption
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         using multipart upload (chunk size = 100 MB)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Register the case in the metadata store.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This record tracks the video through the entire analysis pipeline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     write to DynamoDB table "surgical-cases":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         case_id          = case_metadata.case_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         procedure_type   = case_metadata.procedure_type    // e.g., "laparoscopic_cholecystectomy"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         surgeon_id       = case_metadata.surgeon_id        // de-identified for research pipelines
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         video_key        = video_key
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         upload_timestamp = current UTC timestamp
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         analysis_status  = "PENDING"                       // will progress through PROCESSING → COMPLETE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         video_duration   = case_metadata.duration_minutes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Start the analysis pipeline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     start Step Functions execution with input:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         case_id   = case_metadata.case_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         video_key = video_key
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         procedure_type = case_metadata.procedure_type
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN case_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 2: Video preprocessing and frame extraction.** Raw surgical video needs normalization before analysis. Different OR systems produce different formats, resolutions, and frame rates. This step standardizes everything and extracts frames at the sampling rate needed for the ML models. It also detects and marks non-surgical segments (camera outside the body, blank screens) so the models don't waste compute on irrelevant frames. Skip this step and your models will spend GPU cycles analyzing title cards and blank screens, and inconsistent resolutions will degrade feature extraction quality.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION preprocess_and_extract_frames(case_id, video_key, sampling_rate_fps):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Transcode to a standard format.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Input might be H.264, H.265, MPEG-4, or proprietary.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Output is always H.264 at 1080p, 25fps for consistency.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     create MediaConvert job:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         input  = S3 object at video_key
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         output = S3 "processed-videos/{case_id}/normalized.mp4"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         settings:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             codec       = H.264
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             resolution  = 1920x1080
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             frame_rate  = 25
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Extract frames at the specified sampling rate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // For phase recognition, 1 fps is standard (captures temporal patterns without excess compute).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // For tool detection, 5 fps may be needed (tools move fast).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     create MediaConvert job:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         input  = S3 "processed-videos/{case_id}/normalized.mp4"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         output = S3 "frames/{case_id}/frame_%06d.jpg"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         settings:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             output_type   = frame_capture
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             capture_rate  = sampling_rate_fps    // typically 1 frame per second
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             format        = JPEG
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             quality       = 95                   // high quality; compression artifacts hurt feature extraction
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Generate a frame manifest listing all extracted frames with timestamps.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     frame_manifest = list all frames in S3 "frames/{case_id}/"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each frame in frame_manifest:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         frame.timestamp_seconds = frame_number / sampling_rate_fps
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     write frame_manifest to S3 "frames/{case_id}/manifest.json"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Update case status.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     update DynamoDB "surgical-cases" where case_id:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         analysis_status = "FRAMES_EXTRACTED"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         frame_count     = length of frame_manifest
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN frame_manifest
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Spatial feature extraction.** This is the computationally expensive step. Each sampled frame is passed through a pretrained CNN or vision transformer to produce a compact feature vector (typically 2048 dimensions for ResNet-50 or 768 for ViT-Base). These feature vectors encode the visual content of each frame in a form that the temporal model can reason about. Running this on GPU is essential; CPU inference would take hours per procedure. The model is pretrained on ImageNet and fine-tuned on surgical data to recognize surgery-specific visual patterns (instruments, tissue types, anatomical landmarks).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION extract_spatial_features(case_id, frame_manifest):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Load the spatial backbone model.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This is a CNN (e.g., ResNet-50) or vision transformer (e.g., ViT-B/16)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // pretrained on ImageNet, then fine-tuned on surgical frame classification.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // The final classification layer is removed; we use the penultimate layer's output
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // as a feature vector (2048-dim for ResNet-50, 768-dim for ViT-B/16).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     model = load_model("spatial-backbone-surgical-v2")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Process frames in batches for GPU efficiency.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Batch size depends on GPU memory; 32-64 frames per batch is typical for ml.g5.xlarge.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     feature_vectors = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     batches = split frame_manifest into chunks of 32
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each batch in batches:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Load and preprocess frames.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Preprocessing: resize to model input size (224x224 or 384x384),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // normalize pixel values to ImageNet mean/std.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         frames = load and preprocess images from S3 for each frame in batch
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Run inference. Output is a batch of feature vectors.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features = model.predict(frames)    // shape: [batch_size, feature_dim]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         append features to feature_vectors
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Save feature vectors as a single file for the temporal model.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Shape: [num_frames, feature_dim] — e.g., [2700, 2048] for a 45-min video at 1fps
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     write feature_vectors to S3 "features/{case_id}/spatial_features.npy"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     update DynamoDB "surgical-cases" where case_id:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         analysis_status = "FEATURES_EXTRACTED"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN path to spatial_features file
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 4: Temporal modeling and phase prediction.** The temporal model takes the sequence of feature vectors and produces per-frame predictions. For phase recognition, each frame gets a predicted phase label and confidence score. The temporal model captures patterns like "dissection always comes before clipping" and "if we've been in dissection for 10 minutes, we're probably still in dissection." This is where the system goes from understanding individual frames to understanding the procedure as a narrative.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION predict_phases(case_id, features_path, procedure_type):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Load the temporal model appropriate for this procedure type.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Different procedures have different phase definitions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // A cholecystectomy model knows 7 phases; a sleeve gastrectomy model knows different phases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     temporal_model = load_model("temporal-{procedure_type}-v3")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Load the feature sequence.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features = load numpy array from S3 at features_path
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Shape: [num_frames, feature_dim]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Run temporal inference.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Input: sequence of feature vectors
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Output: per-frame phase probabilities
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     phase_probabilities = temporal_model.predict(features)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Shape: [num_frames, num_phases] — probability distribution over phases for each frame
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Convert probabilities to predictions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     predictions = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each frame_idx in range(num_frames):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         predicted_phase = argmax(phase_probabilities[frame_idx])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         confidence      = max(phase_probabilities[frame_idx])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         predictions.append({
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             frame_index: frame_idx,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             timestamp:   frame_idx * sampling_interval,    // seconds into the video
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             phase:       PHASE_NAMES[procedure_type][predicted_phase],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             confidence:  confidence,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             all_probs:   phase_probabilities[frame_idx]    // keep full distribution for analysis
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         })
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN predictions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 5: Post-processing and event detection.** Raw frame-level predictions are noisy. A single frame might be predicted as "clipping" in the middle of a long dissection segment. Post-processing smooths these predictions using temporal filtering and transition constraints. It also detects higher-level events by analyzing the phase timeline: unusually long phases, rapid phase transitions (which might indicate complications), and specific patterns of clinical interest.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION postprocess_and_detect_events(predictions, procedure_type):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Step 5a: Temporal smoothing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Apply a median filter to remove isolated mispredictions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Window size of 15 frames (15 seconds at 1fps) is typical.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     smoothed = apply_median_filter(predictions.phases, window=15)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Step 5b: Transition constraint enforcement.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Some phase transitions are impossible (you can't go from "preparation" to "extraction"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // without passing through dissection and clipping). Enforce valid transitions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     valid_transitions = TRANSITION_MATRIX[procedure_type]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     corrected = enforce_transitions(smoothed, valid_transitions)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Step 5c: Segment extraction.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Convert frame-level predictions into contiguous segments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     segments = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     current_phase = corrected[0]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     segment_start = 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each frame_idx, phase in corrected:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF phase != current_phase:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             segments.append({
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 phase:      current_phase,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 start_time: segment_start * sampling_interval,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 end_time:   frame_idx * sampling_interval,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 duration:   (frame_idx - segment_start) * sampling_interval,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 confidence: mean confidence for frames in this segment
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             })
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             current_phase = phase
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             segment_start = frame_idx
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Step 5d: Event detection.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Analyze the phase timeline for clinically significant patterns.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     events = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Detect unusually long phases (potential difficulty indicators).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     phase_duration_norms = EXPECTED_DURATIONS[procedure_type]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each segment in segments:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF segment.duration > phase_duration_norms[segment.phase] * 2.0:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             events.append({
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 type:       "extended_phase",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 phase:      segment.phase,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 duration:   segment.duration,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 expected:   phase_duration_norms[segment.phase],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 timestamp:  segment.start_time,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 severity:   "informational"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             })
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Detect rapid phase oscillation (may indicate uncertainty or complication).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF count_transitions_in_window(corrected, window=60) > 4:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         events.append({
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             type:      "rapid_transitions",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             timestamp: window_start_time,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             severity:  "review_recommended"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         })
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         segments: segments,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         events:   events,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         total_duration: sum of all segment durations,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         phase_summary: { phase: total_duration for each unique phase }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 6: Store results and index for search.** The final step persists the analysis results and indexes them for discovery. Surgeons and quality teams need to find cases by characteristics: "show me all cholecystectomies where dissection exceeded 20 minutes" or "find cases with detected events." The full frame-level predictions go to S3 (they're large), while summaries and searchable attributes go to DynamoDB and OpenSearch.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION store_and_index_results(case_id, segments, events, phase_summary):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Store full results to S3 (too large for DynamoDB).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     write to S3 "analysis-results/{case_id}/full_results.json":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         segments      = segments           // complete phase timeline
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         events        = events             // detected events
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         phase_summary = phase_summary      // duration per phase
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         model_version = "temporal-cholecystectomy-v3"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         analysis_timestamp = current UTC timestamp
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Update case metadata with summary.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     update DynamoDB "surgical-cases" where case_id:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         analysis_status   = "COMPLETE"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         analysis_timestamp = current UTC timestamp
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         total_phases       = count of unique phases in segments
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         total_events       = count of events
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         longest_phase      = phase with maximum duration
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         longest_phase_duration = maximum phase duration
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         has_review_events  = any event with severity == "review_recommended"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Index in OpenSearch for flexible search.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     index in OpenSearch "surgical-analysis":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         case_id         = case_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         procedure_type  = procedure_type
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         surgeon_id      = surgeon_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         analysis_date   = current date
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         phase_durations = phase_summary          // enables "dissection > 20 min" queries
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         events          = events                 // enables event-type filtering
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         total_duration  = total procedure duration
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         event_count     = count of events
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         review_needed   = has_review_events
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN { case_id: case_id, status: "COMPLETE", events_detected: count of events }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter09.09-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Expected Results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sample output for a laparoscopic cholecystectomy:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```json
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "case_id": "CASE-2026-03-15-0847",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "procedure_type": "laparoscopic_cholecystectomy",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "total_duration_minutes": 47.2,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "phase_summary": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "preparation": 3.1,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "calot_triangle_dissection": 22.4,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "clipping_and_cutting": 2.8,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "gallbladder_dissection": 12.1,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "gallbladder_packaging": 1.9,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "cleaning_coagulation": 3.2,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "specimen_extraction": 1.7
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "segments": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     { "phase": "preparation", "start": 0, "end": 186, "confidence": 0.94 },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     { "phase": "calot_triangle_dissection", "start": 186, "end": 1530, "confidence": 0.88 },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     { "phase": "clipping_and_cutting", "start": 1530, "end": 1698, "confidence": 0.91 }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "events": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "type": "extended_phase",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "phase": "calot_triangle_dissection",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "duration_minutes": 22.4,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "expected_minutes": 12.0,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "severity": "informational"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "model_version": "temporal-cholecystectomy-v3",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "analysis_status": "COMPLETE"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    465[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Performance benchmarks:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    466[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    467[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Metric | Typical Value |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    468[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |--------|---------------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    469[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Phase recognition accuracy | 85–92% (frame-level, Cholec80 benchmark) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    470[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Phase recognition accuracy (relaxed, ±10s) | 92–96% |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    471[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Tool detection mAP | 80–90% (7-tool cholecystectomy setup) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    472[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | End-to-end latency (batch) | 8–15 minutes per 60-minute procedure |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    473[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | End-to-end latency (real-time) | 2–5 seconds per frame (with GPU endpoint) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    474[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Cost per procedure (batch) | $2.50–$8.00 (GPU inference + storage) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    475[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Cost per procedure (real-time) | $15–$40 (persistent GPU endpoint amortized) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    476[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    477[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Where it struggles:** Procedures with significant deviation from standard technique (adhesions from prior surgery, anatomical variants, conversion to open). Smoke-heavy segments where visibility is severely degraded. Procedures outside the training distribution (the model trained on cholecystectomies knows nothing about appendectomies). Low-confidence transitions between phases where the visual distinction is subtle.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    478[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    479[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    480[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    481[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Why This Isn't Production-Ready
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    482[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    483[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Regulatory pathway.** Any system that provides clinical feedback (even "this phase seems long") during a live procedure is likely a medical device requiring FDA clearance. Retrospective analysis for quality review has a lower regulatory bar, but the line is blurry. Get regulatory counsel involved early.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    484[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    485[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Video acquisition integration.** Getting video out of the OR and into your pipeline reliably is a systems integration challenge. OR video systems are often proprietary, not designed for automated export, and managed by biomedical engineering teams with their own priorities. Plan for 3-6 months of integration work.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    486[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    487[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Model generalization.** A model trained on Cholec80 (European academic center, specific surgeons, specific equipment) may not generalize to your institution's videos (different camera systems, different surgical styles, different patient populations). Plan for local fine-tuning with your own annotated data.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    488[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    489[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Consent and governance.** Surgical video contains identifiable information (patient anatomy, surgeon technique). Research use requires IRB approval. Clinical use requires clear governance policies about who can access videos, how long they're retained, and how they're used. This is a policy problem as much as a technical one.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    490[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    491[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    492[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    493[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Honest Take
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    494[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    495[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Surgical video analysis is one of those fields where the research papers look incredible and the production reality is humbling. The Cholec80 benchmark numbers (90%+ accuracy) come from a curated dataset of 80 videos from a single center with consistent equipment and technique. Deploy the same model at a different hospital with different cameras, different surgeons, and patients with BMIs above 40, and accuracy drops 10-15 points.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    496[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    497[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The part that surprised me most: the hardest problem isn't the ML. It's getting the video. OR video systems are designed for live display, not for automated export. The DICOM standard for video (DICOM-SR, DICOM encapsulated video) exists but is inconsistently implemented. Many ORs still record to local hard drives or USB sticks. Building a reliable, automated video pipeline from OR to cloud is a multi-month infrastructure project that has nothing to do with machine learning.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    498[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    499[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The phase recognition models are genuinely useful for retrospective quality analysis even at 85% accuracy. You don't need perfect frame-level predictions to answer "which cases had unusually long dissection phases?" A 15-second error in phase boundary detection doesn't matter when you're looking at 20-minute phases. The value is in aggregate patterns, not frame-perfect annotation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    500[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    501[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Real-time intraoperative use is a different story. Latency requirements are strict (you need predictions within seconds, not minutes), the cost of a wrong prediction is higher (a false "critical view achieved" signal could lead to premature clipping), and the regulatory bar is much higher. I'd start with retrospective analysis and build confidence before attempting real-time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    502[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    503[0m:[38;5;10m[49m One more thing: surgeon buy-in is everything. If surgeons perceive this as surveillance or performance monitoring, adoption will be zero regardless of technical quality. Frame it as education, quality improvement, and research. The institutions that have succeeded with surgical video AI are the ones where surgeons championed the initiative, not where administrators imposed it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    504[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    505[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    506[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    507[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Variations and Extensions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    508[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    509[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-specific tracking and usage analytics.** Beyond detecting which tools are present, track their usage patterns across cases. Which surgeons use energy devices more? Is there a correlation between instrument changes and procedure duration? This requires per-frame tool detection (not just presence/absence) and builds a rich dataset for surgical technique analysis.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    510[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    511[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Critical view of safety (CVS) assessment.** For cholecystectomy specifically, automatically assess whether the critical view of safety criteria are met before clipping. This is the highest-value clinical application because bile duct injuries (the most feared complication) correlate with failure to achieve CVS. Several research groups and startups are pursuing this specific application, and it's likely to be among the first FDA-cleared surgical video AI products.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    512[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    513[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-procedure expansion.** The architecture described here works for any procedure with defined phases. Extend to sleeve gastrectomy, appendectomy, hernia repair, or robotic prostatectomy by training procedure-specific temporal models. The spatial backbone can often be shared across procedures (surgical instruments look similar regardless of the operation), but the temporal model must be procedure-specific because phase definitions differ.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    514[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    515[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    516[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    517[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Related Recipes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    518[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    519[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 9.7 (Radiology AI Triage - Multi-Modality):** Shares the pattern of processing large medical media files through ML pipelines with clinical integration challenges
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    520[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 9.1 (Image Quality Assessment):** The frame quality assessment component of surgical video preprocessing uses similar quality scoring approaches
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    521[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 12.10 (Physiological Waveform Analysis):** Shares the temporal modeling pattern (sequence of measurements over time analyzed for patterns and events)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    522[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 9.8 (Pathology Slide Analysis):** Similar challenge of processing very large medical media (gigapixel images vs. hour-long videos) with tiled/sampled approaches
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    523[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
